Comment:
An hour of, what could have been really good scenes, just to find out what you knew all along, *sequel* .
The gas station scene with James Franco's character Taylor, could have been much better with more of Jame's great facial 
expressions instead of the scene time being wasted on the dirty linoleum floor. 
This might give you a good indication of how this movie went.
Another Taylor scene were the cop shoots, but can't break through the bullet proof glass.
Taylor puts the gun underneath and fires. I thought Jame's held the scene well, 
but I couldn't help but feel that this cop must have been the most ill trained or stupid person on the planet.
Why, the cop might have thought to move or duck like every one else had .
She had time . 
For the first almost hour, the movie plodded along , and you couldn't help but think,
" Isn't this movie about some high tech futuristic gun " ? 
Oh, yes Arnold rode a bike, but we understood his certain limitations.
These future cats can find cracks and move through time and they have cool ass shit,
so I was a little taken back when I saw them on foot.
And that's the caveat here folks. Kin doesn't move enough and I wasn't drawn into any of the characters enough
to have feelings for them,so as  to make these mistakes by the director palatable.
One thing, why would you ever leave Taylor alive in the first place.
His gun was out of bullets.
If Jack Reynor's character Jimmy, had time to get up and run, he would have time to use the hammer.
Was his gun out of bullets ? 
The club scene. Who in their right mind would ever bring that whole bag into a club that you knew nothing about,
I have to stop there. That was frustrating.
Lay low wasn't part of their dialect. WHAT 
 OK, if that's the case, seeing that they went to a place were there's more cameras than anyplace in the world,
at least give the movie momentum , some juice , some speed. 
BTW, more movies with *Zo√´ Kravitz*  She's just not beautiful, she can make a scene have life where there is none.
Dennis Quad did a great job as the hard dad. Very believable.
I think the director went in the wrong direction, I should say directions , because at times I was a bit confused at which way the movie was going.
For instance. Taylor and the burial. 
That was some Lost Boys , _Come out and Play _ shit. Stabbed him six times.
OK, the lets go surreal , then we went back to another scene of , well......
I will go see Kin ll is they make another, but I won't re-watch Kin. 
This is the directors fault .

Title: KIN (2018 Movie) Official Trailer - Dennis Quaid, Zo√´ Kravitz
Comment:
The issue I get from this is that the movie events shown in the trailers seems all around the place.

First, there's an insane chance that half of what people feel while watching the trailer comes from the soundtrack used in the trailer that won't be in the actual movie. The "epic" track used in this trailer is a custom version (made especially for this trailer) of a soundtrack that is relatively common for action-based trailer of movies. (Yeah, there are quite a few studios/groups who create soundtracks especially for trailers such as 2 Steps from Hell, Posthumus, Adiemus, Really Slow Motion (who hired compositors around the globe), etc. Those studios focus the composition to provoke a feeling while watching the trailer (action = adrenaline, drama = sadness, family = laugh, etc.)

The trick to counter this 100% fake side of the trailer is to turn off the volume. This is much closer to the actual movie because, in reality, movies actually has limited soundtracks and, even in the most action-oriented movies, barely a third (1/3) of the movie has the same kind of soundtrack as in the trailer. This also allow you to put more effort in your sense of view and recognition which allows you to see how boring/simple the movie might actually be.

From what I can see in this trailer, I get, from this trailer, the same kind of feeling as I had from the movie Blank Check. Take a kid, give him something many adults wants (including criminals), put some family pressure/issues in the mix and let the scenario run on the power generated from that chemical mix. This means it's clearly not a movie made with, in mind, some long terms entertainment and the sequel, if it has any, will only drop the ball further. It doesn't mean that the movie is bad, but let's say that it seems they focused on the wrong part of the movie which is the gun way too much and not enough on developing the characters surrounding the gun's story.
